A consequence of [Brouwer's constructivism](constructivism), it's "logic as if people mattered": a proposition is only true if it has a proof (not a *formal proof* -- these are dodgy as per Goedel). 

## Negative Fragment

$\frac{\;}{T\:prop}$ -- trivially true proposition (truth formation)

$\frac{\;}{T\:true}$ -- trivially true proposition is true

there is no "truth elimination" -- we can't eliminate a proof

$\frac{A\:prop\;B\:prop}{A\wedge B\:prop}$ -- conjunction introduction

$\frac{A\:true\;\;B\:true}{A\wedge B\:true}$

$\frac{A\wedge B\:true}{A\:true}$ $\frac{A\wedge B\:true}{B\:true}$

$\frac{A\:prop\;B\:prop}{A\rightarrow B\:prop}$

$\frac{A\:true\vdash B\:true}{A\rightarrow B\:true}$

$\frac{A\rightarrow B\:true\;A\:true}{B\:true}$ -- modus ponens

Logical entailment ($\vdash$) is prior to implication ($\rightarrow$).

